Text: So this week has been filled with a lot of uncertainty.
After being assigned to our group we had a group meeting over Zoom to discuss which project we were going to pitch for.
After some back and forth we decided on the soil mapping project.
We decided on this project because of the different elements in it as well as Kuku from Logic Studio being one of the clients this will make for a good learning experience.
The brief for this project explains that we are to allow potential customers to search for aggregates near their location and request a price to have it supplied and delivered.
The customers will use a map to search for nearby materials.

The project seems to involve using a database and integrating it with a web page displaying a map using PHP which is something that I haven't touched for many years, so will be good to have a refresher in that.
We will also need to find a way to import the data from different sources into the database.
Our pitch for the project went okay, it would have been better if we had researched the topics a little further.
This project has 2 clients.Kuku from Logic Studio and Eric Dance from Alliance Trucking.
Eric is a client of Kukus. Our project is just a small part in the overall project that Kuku is working on for Eric.
We met with our clients on Thursday to find out a little bit more about what we are doing.
We found out a little bit more about Erics business and how it works.
Allience works as a middleman and connects freelance truckers to his customers that are looking to acquire different aggregates and then finds a source to retrieve those materials.
Eric and Kuku have already put together a spreadsheet of different data sources that contain information about suppliers.
It is suggested that we start with the information provided by MSHA (Mine Safety and Health Administration).

MSHA has a lot of information about quarries all over the USA, and we can get more detailed information about suppliers in specific states later as there is a lot of data sources in potentially different formats that will make sifting through the data more tedious.
So for now we will focus on the MSHA data so that we can get a working prototype.
During our meeting we received technical advice from Kuku.
His preference is that we work using PHP and use MySQL for the database, as that's what he is using for the rest of the project so this will make it easier to integrate in.

As for the maps, we could use the Google Maps API but it has a limit on how much traffic it can get before it needs to be paid for so we may need to look into different map suppliers such as OpenStreetMap.
Eric has shared the spreadsheet containing the data sources with us, so we have been spending time sifting around the data to see what kind of data it contains and the formats that it is in.
Our goal for the upcoming week will mainly do research for and complete our proposal.
We will also work on our database design and hopefully get that implemented and start putting the data in as well.
